response.message:
@athos Read this article: http://www.inc.com/magazine/20090401/how-hard-could-it-be-employees-negotiate-pay-raises.html

Basically, when you get a job offer, they will work with you to establish the level you're at, and your salary will be set by that level. Every developer at a given level gets the same salary, and it's intended to be completely non-negotiable.

The level-to-salary table is not public information, as far as I know. So the only way you'll know what salary you'll get is to get a job offer from them.

@JM I am so sorry to hear that you experienced trauma in the workplace. I agree that having your back in the open is a vulnerable position.

I understand the rationale behind the positioning, so that people walking around in the corridors are less of a distraction, but, if it makes you feel vulnerable or triggered, then it's definitely more of a distraction, not less.

If you plan to apply to Stack Exchange, you should definitely make that a known point. You may opt to work remotely from home, if they don't have an office arrangement that would make you feel safe.
